title: For Sale:  Ejercito Argentino Model 1927 45 Auto (1911 clone) for sale
postcontent:
Taking offers on my 1911 clone. Frame is an officer size. Slide is a commander size. New recoil spring has been installed.
Here's a little history of this model.
There were only 10,000 of these pistols made by Colt for the Argentine Army (Ejercito Argentino) under contract in 1927. The pistol is basically a '1911A1' (post 1924) configuration and featured a World War I style (Pre-A1 version) wide spur hammer withcheckering, short checkered trigger and a checkered (arched) mainspring housing with lanyard loop. All of these Colts had a deep blue finish. Production is said to have begun in July, 1927 and ended in February, 1928. After the initial 10,000 units were produced, the Argentine government purchased a license to build the 'Model 1927' pistol in Argentina under the markings 'FMAP' which stood for 'Fabrica Militar de Armas Portatiles'.

title: For Sale:  SPENCER MODEL 1860 .52 CAL. CIVIL WAR CARBINE
postcontent: Authentic, All Original, Antique Spencer Model 1860 Civil War 52 Cal. Metallic Rim Fire Carbine, also known as the “No. 56,” or “56-56.” (Referred to in modern times by collectors as the “50 Caliber.”) Not a conversion with the Stabler “cut off” device. All original. Un-altered. Not been tampered with. 7+1 Rim Fire cartridge capacity through the butt stock to the chamber. Lever action repeating rifle. The Model 1860 was manufactured from 1863-1865 (according to the serial number, this rifle was made in 1863). 22” barrel. Six groove rifling (the post-Civil War altered conversions with Stabler device were three groove rifling and those made by Burnside Rifle Company in Providence, Rhode Island). Sling swivel at butt stock (an original factory feature). Only 45,785 were made in 1863. Low 5 digit serial number 25791 (the serial numbers started at 11,000 and went up to 61,000). Stock shows combat use. Metal ok condition. Bore ok. Mechanically good. Full functional. Very rare Civil War collectible. All of these made in 1863 were sent to the battlefield and used in combat, mainly by the North, or Union Cavalry (though some carbines fell into the hands of the South, or Confederacy). After the Civil War this carbine, as well as others like it, remained un-touched and un-altered, and were used by the military and civilians, including the American Indians, outlaws and law enforcement throughout the American West. There is no telling who originally owned this rifle during the Civil War and afterwards. It has quite a history to tell. “If it could only talk”!  (see Flayderman’s Guide p. 633). MORE PICTURES AVAILABLE. FEEL FREE TO CONTACT ME WITH ANY QUESTIONS. CAN SHIP INSURED DIRECTLY TO BUYER.

title: For Sale:  Steyr Model M 30-06 Double Set Triggers
postcontent:
This is a rare Steyr model M chambered in 30-06. It has a 23.622 inch cold hammer forged barrel (600 mm). This rifle is set in the Cycolac synthetic stock and has the standard parkerized finish. The stock and finish are really nice features for hunting. The parkerized coating is highly corrosion resistant and the synthetic stock is resilient to inclement weather. The stock has nice checkering on it to ensure a good grip even when wet, while maintaining a more traditional appearance than the typical synthetic stock.

The Steyr model M never sold all that well in this country, and it seems that virtually all of the ones available here come with a standard single trigger. This one has double set triggers. You have two modes in which to shoot. If you are at the range and desire an extremely light pull, you pull the rear trigger first. Pulling the rear trigger sets the front trigger to a very light weight, allowing you to be more accurate at the range. However, a very light pull weight can be hazardous when hunting. With double set triggers, you don't have to worry about a hair trigger. When hunting, you can simply pull the front trigger and have a normal trigger pull. The double set triggers allows you to have the best of both worlds; a hair trigger for target shooting at the range and a normal (good) trigger pull when hunting.

This particular rifle also has a rare set of quick-detachable scope mounts and rings. This is very convenient, as you can remove the scope and mounts instantly for ease of cleaning the rifle from the breech. Then, you can place the mount and scope back on the rifle and be very close (if not exactly) at your previous zero point. These mounts and rings are worth about $200 and are very difficult to find.

The rifle is in used-very good condition. This Rifle has seen very minimal use. It has a small nick in the plastic in the tang area. Though not significant, I wanted to bring it to your attention anyway.

The bolt is remarkably smooth and the triggers are very crisp. This rifle has a very similar bolt design to the SSG-69, so it is capable of outstanding accuracy when in good hands. It points and balances very well, weighing only about 8.25 pounds with a scope on it. This would be the perfect gun to take hunting in the mountains, forest, or over rough terrain.

Armslist only allows three attached pictures, but I have a lot more. Please contact me via email to get the rest of the pictures. This rifle is a very nice shooter, you will enjoy it. I would prefer a local sale (either in the Seattle area or the Spokane area), but will ship at buyer's expense. I live in the Spokane area, but will be back in Seattle over Thanksgiving weekend and Christmas.

title: For Sale:  REMINGTON R-25 308 AR PRECISION HUNTING RIFLE
postcontent:
I have to unfortunately go back to a bolt action rifle for hunting because I am going back to Canada to hunt and Canada doesn't allow semi auto rifles into their country.  I have used this Remington R25 for the last two years to hunt with in Oregon and it has been a fantastic rifle.  I would not be going back to my Weatherby if I didn't have to after using a semi auto to hunt with, they are such an improvement over bolt actions.  This rifle has been a tack driver, and I took a nice 5x5 elk last year with it.  

****Nightforce optic and bipid are not included****

The specs on this rifle are as follows:

The Remington R-25 is an advanced, highly lethal blend of accuracy, fast followups and light recoil chambered in 308 Win.  For peak accuracy, its precision crafted 20" ChroMoly barrel is free floated within the machined aluminum fore-end tube.   Six longitudinal flutes forward of the gas block keep weight to a minimum and facilitate rapid heat dissipation.  The barrel also features a recessed hunting crown to protect the rifling and aid in more consistent bullet flight.  When it's time to make the shot, the R-25's ergonomic pistol grip gives you unmatched control and rock steady aim.  As a whole, this rifle has a balanced, stable design that makes it deadly from the offhand position.  True to our hunting market, the traditional two state trigger found on AR platform rifles has been exchanged for a crisp single stage version that comes from the factory set at 4.5 to 5 lbs.  

Its carefully tuned upper and lower are machined from rugged aluminum forgings.  The entire gun is dressed in Mossy Oak Treestand camo that makes it virtually invisible in the field.  Included is a 20 round magazine and the rifle is compatible with both DPMS and Magpul magazines.  Front and rear sling swivel studs are installed.  

KEY FEATURES
Semi automatic AR-10 style rifle developed in conjunction with an industry leader in the category (DPMS)
Free floated botton rifled 0.680" muzzle OD ChroMoly barrel with recessed hunting crown for superior accuracy
Fluted barrel design reduces weight and promotes rapid barrel cooling 
Clean breaking single stage hunting trigger 
Receiver length picatinny rail for adding optics and accessories 
Ergonomic pistol grip for rock solid aiming and control 

Average weight 7.75 lbs 
308 Win autoloading rifle 
20" carbon steel barrel 
1/10 twist
